SIMPLE: stupefy
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stupefy
<hw>Stu"pe*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Stupefied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Stupefying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>stup⟦eacute⟧fier</ets>, fr. L. <ets>stupere</ets> to be stupefied +
<ets>ficare</ets> (in comp.) to make, akin to <ets>facere</ets>. See
<er>Stupid</er>, <er>Fact</er>, and cf. <er>Stupefacient</er>.]</ety>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>stupify</asp>, especially in England.]</altsp>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To make stupid; to make dull; to blunt the faculty of
perception or understanding in; to deprive of sensibility; to make
torpid.</def><-- temporarily! as by excessive dullness or repetition
-->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The fumes of drink discompose and <qex>stupefy</qex> the
brain.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To deprive of material mobility.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is not malleable; but yet is not fluent, but
<qex>stupefied</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stupendous</ent>⟦br⟧
